# 
## Introduction
The main elements of a workflow are:

- **Tasks**: Activities that the system performs in the running environment, following the rules established by configuring the available parameters for each task type.

> Important

A batch workflow must include at least one final task, i.e. a delivery task (such as the Deliver Emails task) or a storage task (such as the Archive Documents (DA) or the Load Events (TR) tasks). Otherwise, a warning message will be displayed.

> Note

For a comprehensive reference of all available tasks, see: [Doxee Platform Batch Workflows Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-task-reference)

- **Task parameters**: Parameters defining the input data processing rules to create output data that the following task can use, or that is ready for final delivery.

- **Task connectors**: Connections that establish a logical and functional dependency between two tasks.

## Designing a workflow
To define a new workflow, follow these steps:

- Drag &amp; drop the required tasks from the task selection panel into the design area, as described in [Adding a task](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-designing-a-workflow#adding-a-task) below.

- Configure the task parameters, as described in [Configuring a task](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-designing-a-workflow#configuring-a-task) below.

- Connect the tasks, as described in [Connecting tasks](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-designing-a-workflow#connecting-two-tasks) below.

> Note

For more information on the available actions, see [Managing tasks](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-designing-a-workflow#managing-tasks) below.

For more information on the workflow designer user interface, see: [Doxee Platform Batch Workflows - Editor](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-editor).

> Important

It is possible to connect multiple inputs, but only if they all have the same Lot ID, or if only one input has the Assign Lot option enabled.

The engine does not compare lots and fails with an error when getting lots from multiple connections, but it can handle the case when Lot IDs are the same.

### Configuring a task
Select a task and click ![](data:image/png;base64,). The task configuration panel is displayed on the right; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip

You may also double-click on a task to display the task configuration panel.

> Note

If the task configuration is incomplete, or if the task is not properly connected, a warning icon is displayed, for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

For more information, see: [Doxee Platform Batch Workflows Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-task-reference), section "Task configuration".

### Connecting two tasks
This function allows you to connect two tasks in order to create a logical sequence and produce the desired final output.

> Note

The connection between two tasks creates a sequential and hierarchical relationship between the connected tasks. The connection is unidirectional, from left to right.

- Move your mouse over a task. The ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon appears.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

-  Move your mouse over the icon: it becomes red.![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Drag the icon to draw a line to the following task.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

When you reach the box corresponding to the next task, the line becomes dashed.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Release the mouse button. The connection is established.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Disconnecting two tasks
- Select the connection that you want to remove; for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Remove**) on the toolbar.

> Tip

You may also press the **DEL **key to delete the selected element.

### Configuring a connector
- Select a connector and click ![](data:image/png;base64,) . The connector configuration panel is displayed on the right; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- In the **Settings **properties, select the type of **Branch **to assign to the connector. For example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note

It is possible to add multiple output connections to the same branch; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

If the task's branch connection configuration is incomplete, a warning icon is displayed on the connection, for example:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note

For more information on the available branch types for each task, refer to the task's reference page: 

[Doxee Platform Batch Workflows Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-batch-workflows-task-reference)

- [Doxee Platform On-Demand Workflows Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/doxee-platform-on-demand-workflows-task-reference)

- *(optional) *Enable the **Assign lot **option to identify all tasks in the workflow after this branch under a single Lot ID; for example:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Warning

This option should not be enabled immediately before a delivery task, not only because it would disrupt the analytics, but also because it would cause duplicate submissions if the delivery task needs to be resumed.

> Important

This option is mandatory if you want to use the Enrich Analytics (Pvideo/Pweb) tasks in a workflow.

For more information, see:

[Enrich Analytics (Pvideo) Batch Workflow Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/enrich-analytics-pvideo-batch-workflow-task-reference-1)

- [Enrich Analytics (Pweb) Batch Workflow Task Reference](/doxee-platform/docs/enrich-analytics-pweb-batch-workflow-task-reference)

- *(optional) *In the **Filter **field (only available for some tasks), you may enter one or more filename patterns to define filtering rules for the files and folders that will be passed on to the next task in the workflow.

> Note

Of the previous task's output, only the files and folders matching the defined rules will be passed on to the next task in the application chain.

Filters can be specified as glob patterns. If no filters are specified, then all files are passed on to the next task. 

For example, you may want to include only XML files in the HTTP response of an [on-demand workflow](/doxee-platform/docs/on-demand-workflow-resource-reference):

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Duplicating a task or a section of a workflow
This function allows to duplicate a task or a section of a workflow, including its configuration.

- Select the task that you want to copy. 

or:

Draw a rectangle around a section of the workflow.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Tip

You may select multiple tasks by holding down the **SHIFT **key (or ****on macOS) and clicking on the required tasks.

> Note

The selected task(s) will be highlighted in a darker colors. Any selected connectors will display grips at each end. For example: 

Before the selection

![](data:image/png;base64,)

After the selection![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Copy**) on the toolbar.

> Tip

You may also click **CTRL+C **(or **** **+C**).

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Paste**) to paste the task(s) in the design area.

> Tip

You may also click **CTRL+V **(or **** **+V**).

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Deleting a task or a section of a workflow
- Select the task(s) or section of a workflow that you want to delete.

- Click ![](data:image/png;base64,) (**Remove**) on the toolbar.

> Tip

You may also press the **DEL **key to delete the selected element.

### Rearranging task(s) in the workflow
- Select one or more tasks.

- Drag the boxes to a different position in the design area.

> Note

The position of the boxes will automatically snap to the dot grid; red magnetic lines may be displayed to help you with the alignment.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Release the mouse button to drop the task(s) in the new position. Any connecting lines are modified accordingly.

![](data:image/png;base64,)
